We recommended that the LCE require:

The Inventory Committee to prepare the RPCLRN as of December 31, 2019 using the form prescribed in Annex C of COA Circular No. 2015-008, copy furnished the Auditor;

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain complete set of LRNLCs and LRNPCs for each road network component using the forms prescribed in Annex D and E, respectively, of the abovementioned circular;

The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO with complete data relating to the description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and

The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management require the:
Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to reconcile their records of the PPE accounts and make the necessary adjustments thereto;
Further, for both officials to maintain complete PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, in accordance with the forms prescribed in Annexes 9 and 37 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II. Henceforth, conduct periodic reconciliation of their respective records, at least on a quarterly basis, to ensure accuracy of the PPE accounts;
Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties. Thereafter, prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form, i.e per PPE classification and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and
GSO to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) of the identified unserviceable properties as initial step in the disposal thereof.  Thereafter, proceed with the disposal of the same in accordance with existing regulations in order that only serviceable properties remain in the books as PPE.

We recommended that Management, through the Accounting Office, ensure the completeness of documents to support the validity and propriety of transactions. We also recommended to submit the following documents for us to complete our audit:
Official Receipt issued by the Philippine National Police and/or Deed of Acceptance of the procured firearms;
Sales/Delivery Invoice and Official Receipt from the supplier of firearms;
License or certificate of registration; and
Property Acknowledgment Receipt.

We recommended that Management require the:

Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to reconcile their records of the PPE accounts and make the necessary adjustments thereto;

Further, for both officials to maintain complete PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, in accordance with the forms prescribed in Annexes 9 and 37 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II. Henceforth, conduct periodic reconciliation of their respective records, at least on a quarterly basis, to ensure accuracy of the PPE accounts;

Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties. Thereafter, prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year; and

GSO to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) of the identified unserviceable properties as initial step in the disposal thereof.  Thereafter, proceed with the disposal of the same in accordance with existing regulations in order that only serviceable properties remain in the books as PPE.

We recommended that Management:

Designate specific personnel to work on the transfer of the titles of the 67 lots in the name of the Municipality;

Appropriate funds in the LGU’s annual budget to cover related costs in the registration of the real properties;

Require the Inventory Team to prepare a complete inventory report of PPEs, including the real properties, and reconcile the report with the GSO records. Thereafter, furnish the Audit Team a copy of the report;

Instruct the GSO to indicate in the RPCPPE complete information relative to these lots to facilitate the reconciliation of the report with the accounting records; and

Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to maintain Real Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively, for each real property owned by the Municipality.  Further, for both officials to reconcile their subsidiary records regularly, to ensure correctness of the accounts.

We recommended that:

The GSO keep a complete and updated Local Road Network Property Cards (LRNPCs) to serve as a means of checking the accuracy of the Local Road Network Ledger Cards (LRNLCs) maintained by the Municipal Accountant;

Both officials conduct regular reconciliation of the balances of their records, at least on a quarterly basis, to ensure that their records are consistent with each other;

The Municipal Engineer be required to furnish the Municipal Accountant and the GSO complete description and cost segregation of road components for completed road projects as basis for recording in their respective subsidiary records; and

The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendation that the LSB strictly adhere to the proper format prescribed by the DepEd-DBM-DILF JC No. 1, series of 2017, in the computation of the amount available for appropriation for SEF. 

We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:

The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to provide the LSB the certified statement containing the following reports, for the latter to properly compute the amount available for appropriation, namely: (a) actual SEF Income for the immediately preceding fiscal year; (b) actual SEF income for the first two quarters of the current year; (c) the estimated SEF income for the last two quarters of the current year; and (d) the annual estimates for the ensuing year;

Further, for the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to prepare the analysis of surplus as basis in the preparation of the supplemental budget and submit copy thereof to the Auditor for verification;

The LSB the early submission of the complete School Improvement Plans by the school heads, indicating therein the priority needs of the schools based on DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017, together with budget matrix showing its sources, in order that the same may be considered in the preparation of the SEF Budget;

The Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records to arrive at a reliable and accurate SAAOB; and

The personnel concerned to maximize utilization of the Fund.

We recommended that:

Local Chief Executive should be vigilant and refrain from approving expenditures that are not included among the priority expenses chargeable against the SEF;  

The LGU’s/LSB’s Comprehensive Development Plan must bear the approval of the concerned DepEd Division/Regional Office to ensure that it is in accordance with the prevailing policies and guidelines of the DepEd prior to the approval of SEF Budget; 

The Municipal Accountant stop processing payment of activities chargeable against the SEF budget that are not priority program/projects stipulated in DEPED-DBM-DILG Joint Circular (JC) No. 1, s. 2017; and

Further, ensure that complete supporting documents are attached to the disbursement vouchers.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that Management:

Strengthen local planning and facilitate the translation of the local development goals into implementable programs, projects, and activities (PPAs) in local development plans and investment programs;

Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO) and Municipal Engineer to review and evaluate all the unimplemented targeted PPAs included in the current and prior years’ 20% LDF Plans and determine the causes of non-implementation to address the same. Henceforth require them to closely monitor and ensure the efficient implementation of all priority development projects and programs under the 20% LDF that are envisioned to help in the realization of social-economic and environmental benefits.

