We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Prepare a systematic, comprehensive and realistic revenue forecasting system taking into account prior years’ collections and the tax information system of the municipality;
Prepare periodic reports to monitor the status of revenue generation and to serve as guide on the appropriate measures to be adopted in case of shortfall in the projected revenue targets;
Review and reconcile data submitted to the BLGF. Henceforth, ensure completeness, accuracy and timeliness of reports submitted;
Adhere to forecasting guidelines set by BLGF and prepare a counter forecast in case the municipality disagrees with the BLGF local revenue targets; and
In addition, the Municipal Assessor shall regularly provide the MTO with the latest total assessment valuation as well as the taxes to be imposed as bases by the Municipal Treasurer and the Finance Committee for their incoming budget preparation.

We recommended that the Municipal Government:

Comply with the required documents to support the validity and correctness of the honorarium granted and ensure that the requirements in the selection of person/personnel who shall be assigned to special projects particularly in judging, technical support and other support services which requires superior knowledge or expertise in a specific field be fulfilled.;

Prepare a proper, complete and detailed budget program for each activity and the entire Festival for proper/economical allocations of funds;

Oblige the Accounting Unit and the Budget Office to prepare and maintain a separate subsidiary ledger for the Coron Festival fund; and

Ensure that resources of the government be managed, expended or utilized in accordance with laws, rules and regulations to safeguard against loss or wastage of funds.

We recommended that Management:

Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Treasurer and thereafter to submit to the Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers and payrolls, official receipts, including the corresponding reports of each month on or before the  fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of laws, rules and regulations, as applicable;

Direct the Accountant to strictly comply with the timelines on the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor, within the first ten (10) days of the ensuing month, as required by the abovementioned existing law, rules and regulations;

Look into the possibility of augmenting the Accountant’s Office of personnel from other departments, especially during report preparations and/or allowing them to render overtime, subject to availability of funds, in order to submit the accounts and financial reports on the mandated deadlines; and

 Initiate the necessary administrative and/or criminal action in case of unjustified failure/refusal to effect compliance with the foregoing requirements by subordinate officials.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive (LCE) instruct the Accountant to:

Examine all records for the identification of the officials/employees to whom such balances were deducted from. Then, determine whether all Personal Share deducted from the payroll of officials/employees and Government Share were properly remitted; 

Reconcile the employee’s records with the GSIS, HDMF and PhilHealth offices to trace the affected employees on the said accumulated balances;

Cause the immediate remittance to GSIS, HDMF and PhilHealth for the unremitted premiums/contributions and loan repayments of employees, as warranted by the result of inquiry and reconciliation with the said agencies;

Ensure that all GSIS, HDMF and PhilHealth deductions made from the salaries of the officials/employees are promptly remitted to the respective agencies within the prescribed period set by the abovementioned laws to avoid any charges and penalties; and

Maintain subsidiary ledgers for GSIS and Pag-IBIG premiums/loan payments in accordance with the PPSAS.

We recommended for Management to:

Require the Budget Office to appropriate the amount for GAD activity in accordance with the approved GAD Plan and Budget. Also, in case of changes, require the concerned unit to revise the plan supported with SB Resolution;  

Consider/use HGDG, PIMME and FIMME forms in identifying programs and projects attributed to GAD budget;

Develop priority programs/projects that are in immediate needs and doable to avoid various unimplemented programs;

Discontinue the practice of including the payment of honorarium of DCW in the GAD Plan and Budget as well as in the Accomplishment Report and follow rules and regulations stipulated in the PCW-DILG-DBM- NEDA JMC 2016-01 dated January 12, 2016; and 

Ensure that the GAD plan and budget and GAD accomplishment report focus on activities which are geared towards the achievement of the desired outcomes and goals as identified in the Framework Plan for Women.  The priority areas shall be (1) the promotion of gender-responsive governance, (2) protection and fulfillment of women’s human rights; and (3) promotion of women’s economic empowerment.

