‘We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

1) Direct the ICO-Municipal Treasurer and the ICO-Municipal Accountant to look into the cause/s of these huge discrepancies, through a Memorandum, copy furnished the Audit Team for monitoring purposes and thereafter, make the necessary adjustments, as warranted. Henceforth, both should regularly reconcile their records so that errors could be readily detected and adjusted to ensure reliability of the book balances reconciled with the bank;

2) Direct the ICO-Municipal Accountant, through a Memorandum, copy furnished the Audit Team for monitoring purposes, to prepare and submit the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements on all the depository accounts of the LGU for the whole year of CY 2015 and henceforth, on a timely basis to ensure regular reconciliation of the balances of the accounts, in accordance with Sections 3.2 and 3.4 of COA Circular No. 96-011;

3) Direct ICO-Municipal Accountant, through a Memorandum, copy furnished the Audit Team for monitoring purposes, to maintain a complete subsidiary ledger for the Cash in Bank-Local Currency, Current and Time Deposit Accounts to support its controlling account balances appearing in the books, in accordance with Section 10 of NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II; and

4) In case of continued failure by the ICO-Municipal Accountant to prepare, submit and maintain the same, shall automatically cause the suspension of payment of his or her salaries until he or she shall have complied with the requirement of the Commission and the Audit Team shall be constrained to institute or take appropriate legal action, if warranted.

30) Pursue the approval of the NSWMC of the 10 year SWMP as required under RA No. 9003 to ensure its sustainability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international progress in the area of Solid Waste Management.;

31) Strict implementation of the prescribed procedures and guidelines under R.A. No. 9003 on the solid waste segregation at source, establishment of Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) in the barangays; 

32) Conversion of the Municipality’s dumpsite to an Ecological Park or Sanitary Lardfill (SLF) in compliance with Section 37 and 41 of the Act; and

33) Intensify the SWM information dissemination campaign and enforce all regulations to the extent of imposing penalties for non-compliance.

5) We recommended for the Management to Fully discontinue the practice of granting cash advance for travelling expenses to one (1) official or employee and accommodate the travel expenses of other officials and employees therein.

We also reiterated the following prior year’s audit recommendation that the Management:

6) Require the Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to concemed Accountable Officers (AO) requesting immediate liquidation of cash advance or settlement of the amounts due from them;

7) Shall after the lapse of 30 days after the receipt by the concerned AO of the demand letters and he/she fails to settle the cash advance, the Local Chief Executive (LCE) shall cause the withholding of the payment of any money due the AO;

8) Require the AO handling petty cash fund to liquidate his cash advance at the end of the year and refund the balances, if any, for deposit to the depository bank; and

9) Direct the Municipal Accountant to refrain from granting special cash advance to officials and employees who are not designated disbursing officers.

10) Make the necessary adjusting/correcting entries to properly record the receivables from the employee-beneficiary of the loans, improperly recorded in the General and Trust Funds books starting May 2014 to December 31, 2015, otherwise the Audit Team shall issue Notices of Disallowances on subject transactions improperly recorded in the books of the LGU, without approved appropriations and authority from the Sangguniang Bayan, to transfer subject funds;

